<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Server: Povar<br></font>




	
	<td bgcolor="29003E" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b></b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >My biggest concern ultimately is the effect this will have on groups that ALREADY manage aggro extraordinarilly well.<br />
<br />
Example - Mob is pulled, root parked, debuffed (tash, slow, Mala, whatever).  Warrior Taunts, inherits HATE from all these debuffs AND has aggro because root still in place (providing enough time for 2 taunt attempts).  Taunt is successful, Warrior uses Provoke.<br />
<br />
Simple strategy, yet it gives the Warrior an immense amount of burst aggro, above and beyond any that she generates with weapon swings, procs, augment procs, secondary skills (kick, bash) or buff bonuses.<br />
<br />
In a group of lvl 65s, it would allow a Wizard with SCS3 to safely open with SoS when an average exp mob (such as a PoV golem) is at no less than 97% life (2740 dmg nuke = ~ 2000 "HATE points", minus about 1000 "HATE points" from the debuff aggro the Warrior inherited from taunting, minus 400 "HATE points" from Provoke, and about 1 round of combat damage).<br />
<br />
I know this strategy employs a gimmick (root).  However, it isn't uncommon for debuff classes (slowers) to debuff the target on inc, tank a round (or root), and then have the Warrior (or tank) taunt to inherit aggro.  The addition of Provoke, and additional Aggro generating skills made available when "openings" occur, will only serve to make aggro control a trivial matter.<br />
<br />
I am happy a new melee system is forthcomming.  I am glad Warriors are getting an innate 5% melee damage mitigation bonus to set them back on the top in terms of tanking superiority. <br />
<br />
I do not like the idea of the one thing that makes this game even remotely challenging or strategic becomming trivial.    <img src="images/smilies/mad.gif" border="0" alt=""></font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
	</td>
</tr>
